Introduction¶

IMDB Movie Data:
This dataset contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb),including user ratings and revenue. Not all features are relevant to the questions this analysis is to answer. Therefore, a few will be taken out. Data provided by Udacity
Original data provided by Kaggle

Dataset features:

  • id,
  • imdb_id,
  • popularity,
  • budget,
  • revenue,
  • original_title,
  • cast,
  • homepage,
  • director,
  • tagline,
  • keywords,
  • overview,
  • runtime,
  • genres,
  • production_companies,
  • release_date,
  • vote_count,
  • vote_average,
  • release_year,
  • budget_adj*,
  • revenue_adj

    **The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

Further on data will be explored and analysed to andwer two questions.

Question 1: Is it worth the time to watch movies?* If so, when picking a movie how would one know they won't be disappointed?Conclusion

  • What are the chances of ending up with a good movie? Insight
  • Does it matter when the movie was produced? Insight
  • Which genre(s) are associated with good movies? Insight

    • *It is assumed that you have no prior knowledge about movies. And want to randomly pick a movie out of a list.

    Question 2: Is it a good idea to invest in movie production? If so, how to maximise your chances of success?Conclusion

  • What are the chances of succeeding?Insight
  • Does initial investment guarantee financial success?Insight
  • Does content quality bring in more profit? Insight
  • Which genre(s) are the safest/best bet for investment? Insight

    • Function: fix multiple-value data entries

    In [33]:
    def split_data (input_dataframe, column_to_trim):
    df_to_trim = input_dataframe[input_dataframe[column_to_trim].str.find('|') != -1].copy()
    df_temp = input_dataframe.copy()
    ind = df_to_trim.index
    for i in ind:
        record_to_fix = df_temp.loc[i].copy()
        df_temp.drop([i], axis = 0, inplace = True)
        temp = record_to_fix.copy()
        for j in range(record_to_fix[column_to_trim].count('|')+1):
            temp[column_to_trim] = record_to_fix[column_to_trim].split('|')[j]
            df_temp = df_temp.append(temp)
    return df_temp

    • Fix 0 values
    Columns runtime, budget_adjand revenue_adjhave considerable number of 0 values that will impact the analysis. 0s will be replace by the average value of each column for each genre.

    Fix 0 values for runtime

    In [40]:
    def fix_zero_values(column_name):
    df_movies_temp = df_movies[['id',column_name]].copy()
    #genre is saved in a different dataset. merge datasets first
    df_to_fix = pd.merge(df_genres, df_movies_temp,how = 'inner',left_on = 'id', right_on = 'id')
    #take out zeros so the average will not be affected
    df_to_fix_Nonzero = df_to_fix[df_to_fix[column_name] != 0].copy()
    df_to_fix_zero = df_to_fix[df_to_fix[column_name] == 0].copy()
    #calculate average value of the column for each genre
    average_column_value = (df_to_fix_Nonzero.groupby('genre').mean()[column_name])

    #replace zero values
    for i in df_to_fix_zero.index:
        genre = df_to_fix_zero.loc[i,'genre']
        average_value = average_column_value[genre]
        df_to_fix_zero.loc[i,column_name] = average_value
   
    df_zero_value_fixed = df_to_fix_zero.copy()

    #update values of column_name in movies dataset
    df_movies_index = df_movies[df_movies[column_name] == 0].index
    for i in df_movies_index:
        movie_id = df_movies.loc[i,'id']
        if movie_id in df_zero_value_fixed.id.unique():
            column_value = df_zero_value_fixed[df_zero_value_fixed.id == movie_id][column_name].mean()
            df_movies.loc[i,column_name] = column_value

    Exploratory Data Analysis¶

    In this section data is explored to extract insight and answer question.

    Question 1: Is it worth the time to watch movies? If so, when picking a movie how would one know they won't be disappointed?¶

    . What are the chances of ending up with a good movie?
    . Does it matter when the movie was produced?
    . Which genre(s) are associated with good movies?

    To answer this question, data will be explored with vote_average assigned to each movie. first step would be to label movies as good or bad so as to be able to later group them accordingly and perform the analysis.

    What are the chances of ending up with a good movie?

    #Categorize movies into 'Waste of time', 'Not bad', 'Worth the time' based on vote_average for each movie. 
#Each movie will have an entry in a new column 'review'
df_vote_average = df_movies[['id', 'vote_average']].copy()
df_review_temp = df_vote_average.copy()
vote_ranges = [1,5.5, 7, 9.2]
review_labels = ['Waste of time', 'Not bad', 'Worth the time']
df_review_temp['review'] = pd.cut(df_review_temp['vote_average'], bins = vote_ranges, labels = review_labels)
df_movie_name = df_movies[['id','original_title']].copy()
df_review = pd.merge(df_movie_name,df_review_temp,how = 'inner', left_on = 'id', right_on = 'id')

    Question 1 - Overall Conclusion:¶

    Overall, it seems 1 out of 3 movies that you'd choose will be a total disappointment,regardless of when it was released. To improve the odds, older movies are a safer bet. For example only 1 out of 10 movies released between 1966-1975 is a waste of time.

    Nevertheless, this is by no means an indication that back in the time better movies were produced. The number of older movies in this dataset is significantly lower.Therefore, it cannot be a very reliable sample size. Moreover, people tend to watch old movies only when it is strongly recommended by others, therefore the ones that got reviewed on Imdb perhaps were anyway on the higher end to begin with.

    Genres such as Documentary, History, Animation, Music and Drama appear to be more promising in terms of higher quality content. 50% of Documentary movies are above average and worth one's time and the chances of being totally disappointed is 0.5%. One Genre to avoid would be Horror. There's a 60% chance of ending up with trash and only 1% are worth the time. Unfortunately, there aren't that many options in Documentry/Histoy/Music genre. But with Drama you have many options and only 2 out 10 movies are total trash.

    The overall conclusion would be that with older movies and genres like History, Animation, Music and Drama there's a better chance of being satisfied with the time invested. With any other genre there's a 30-40% chance of total disappointment

    Q2 - Overall Conclusion¶

    Although there's a 17% chance of loss of money in movie production business, it can be considered a profitable business where you make 1-3 times the budget in profits. And profitability differes significantly across genres.
    Safest bet is to invest in TV movies, as there's no loss of money and prospect of mid-high profit can be seen. Another good point about TV movies is that budget needed is lower than many other categories. However, the average profit is not among the highest compared to othe genres. Genres like Animation and Adventure have the highest profits and maximum 2% of movies in these genres experience loss of money. They require higher investment but they sell well. The category to avoid would be Documentry. The genre with lowest average profit. And 70% fail to make considerable profit. While higher ratings are associated with higher profit, not every genre sells well no matter how high quality of a content is produced. But within the genres that sell well, the better the quality, higher the chances of financial success.

    One interesting genre is TV Movies. Though 40% of the movies in this genre are voted by the viewers as waste of time. One would not lose money by producing movies of this genre. So perhaps the right management of distribution means higher sales and therefore higher profit.

    Overall conclusion would be that investment is a profitable business. Safest bet with lower budget required would be producing TV Movies, best bet in case capital is available is to produce Animation or Adventure movies.

    Limitations¶

    Information on adjusted budget and revenue: The data was missing from more than 50% of the records. To fix it, the average value for each genre was canclulated and used. But since that is data manipulation at very larg scale, it might have drastically distorted the findings. For example the relationship between Ratings and Budget/Revenue.
    Genres: most movies are listed under 2-3 different genres. When the calculations are done, they are taken into consideration more than once.
    Number of movies per genre: the number of movies across genres are disproportionately different. As a result, categorizing the quality based on an average vote to which some genres contributed more than others distorts the findings.
    Number of movies per year: Most movies blong to 2006-2015 bucket. Again such difference in proportions causes distortion.
    Number of votes: Different movies had rcieved different number of votes ranging from few hundred to few thousands. Voters participation definitely changes how a movie is rated. Such a big range in number of votes, does nut produce the most reliable rating chart.
